<font color="#FF0000">THE SHADOWS ON THE WALL ARE ST</font><br>
<tt>Wed May 19 20:31:00 US/Eastern 1999
</tt><p>
I feel like I am walking through the memories that continue to echo in an empty room. Just dropped by to visit and the shadows are still here as are the dreams of Glory that never were.<br><br>
The following is from the book, (unedited), Fields of Fire, Dreams of Glory (c), perhaps this is the summer I will finish it.<br><br>
June 26th, 1968, OKINAWA <br>
When I arrived at Okinawa, I ran into Benevedo and Bennet who were also on their way home. I hadn't seen them in thirteen months. They had served their tour of duty with the 3rd Marine Division near the DMZ, but that's another story, another diary that for now, remains written only in their hearts and minds. Perhaps one day they will share with us their fields of fire and their dreams of glory. <br>
We were the fortunate ones, the survivors.  No one else from our old 101 platoon series at MCRD made it back without being killed or seriously wounded. <br>
While I was in Vietnam I realized that I had made a difference.  There are Marines alive today that wouldn't be if I hadn't volunteered for duty, If I hadn't believed in my country and in what we were doing there. Ronald Allen Moore (Bro), gave his life when he volunteered in my place and today his name is etched on that black reflective wall in Washington, D.C. I had a chance to visit that wall a few years back and it had a profound effect on me. The tears I never shed in war, the love I never gave, the moments lost and pains and sorrows shared were all bottled up and released on that day. All Viet Nam veterans should experience such a healing and finally make peace with the past and move on toward the future.... <br>

